      Pump and Dump Organization
   =20
 =20
This is not legal advice or anything, but one good rule of thumb is that if=
 you are on an internet message board looking to hire a hit man, and you en=
d up chatting with an enthusiastic poster who seems like he might do a good=
 job of murdering the person you want murdered, the odds that he is in fact=
 an undercover police officer are nearly 100%. Same with lots of online cri=
mes, though with different probabilities. Are you buying illegal drugs on a=
 message board? You might get the drugs, or you might get arrested, hard to=
 say. Are you buying a missile launcher on a message board? You are definit=
ely getting arrested, nobody is selling a missile launcher on a message boa=
rd,=C2=A0that is cops.The percentage of people on stock pump-and-dump messa=
ge boards who are cops is, I suspect, not that high, but it is=C2=A0rising.=
 Here=E2=80=99s a good story from Australia, where the police and regulator=
s seem to have a much stronger sense of fair play than they do in the U.S.:=
The [Australian Securities and Investments Commission]=C2=A0has taken the u=
nprecedented step of posting a message in a Telegram chat room to warn trad=
ers they may be breaking the law.In a post on Monday at 9.32am on a newly f=
ormed chat group called =E2=80=9CPump and Dump Organization,=E2=80=9D an ac=
count named ASIC posted that =E2=80=9Ccoordinated pumping of shares can be =
illegal=E2=80=9D.=E2=80=9CWe can see all trades and have access to trader i=
dentities. We=E2=80=99re monitoring this platform and we may be investigati=
ng you. You run the risk of a criminal record, including fines of more than=
 $1M and prison time by being involved.=E2=80=9DThe post was not taken seri=
ously. One user said the post was sent by someone =E2=80=9Cfrom another tel=
egram group trying to spook people here. ASIC don=E2=80=99t send messages l=
ike this.=E2=80=9D Another said it was =E2=80=9Cfake ASIC.=E2=80=9DBut an A=
SIC spokesman confirmed the post was genuine, marking new ground for the co=
rporate watchdog. =E2=80=A6Undeterred, the group pressed on. At 9.54am, mem=
bers were told the stock the group was going to pump was YPB Group, which h=
as a market capitalisation of $14 million.=E2=80=9CUSE THE MARKET ORDER AND=
 SEND IT TO THE SKY!!=E2=80=9D the moderator=E2=80=99s post said just befor=
e markets opened for trade.In early trade, the stock leapt 0.2=C2=A2, or 50=
 per cent to 0.6=C2=A2, before closing at 0.5=C2=A2. YPB was previously the=
 subject of booster activity in the ASX Stock Tips Facebook group in July 2=
020 when the moderator of the group told members: =E2=80=9CThis STOCK is ab=
out to FLY. Don=E2=80=99t CRY when it does.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Unclear if they g=
ot arrested or what. Meanwhile if this had happened in the U.S., the Federa=
l Bureau of Investigation would have posted under an account name like =E2=
=80=9Cyolo_crime420,=E2=80=9D and instead of saying =E2=80=9Cthis is the FB=
I, you may be committing a crime, stay safe out there,=E2=80=9D they would =
have said =E2=80=9Chey everyone good pumping but let=E2=80=99s also do some=
 wash sales back and forth to each other, also by the way I am a drug deale=
r so I am hoping to use this pump to launder my money, also are any of you =
looking for a hit man?=E2=80=9D
