om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Overcollateralized stablecoins</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Thursday I <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25302980.283824/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zd=
HVmZi1sb29raW5nLWZvci10ZXRoZXItcy1tb25leQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1bd6053d=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> talked at some length</a> about a way to manufacture a stablecoi=
n =E2=80=94=C2=A0a cryptocurrency that is always worth a dollar =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0out of no ingredients other than Bitcoin (or some other volatile cryp=
tocurrency). The recipe is fairly simple:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: =
decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">You get a Bitcoin.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A Bitco=
in is worth $55,000.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Maybe tomorro=
w it will be worth, like, $52,000, or even $45,000.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">But it won=E2=80=99t be worth less than, say, $25,000.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So you issue (say) 25,000 stablecoin=
s, each worth $1, collateralized by the Bitcoin.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Someone has to put up the other $30,000 to buy the Bitcoin (=
along with the $25,000 from selling the stablecoins). This person=C2=A0is l=
eft with the residual claim on the Bitcoin, i.e., once the 25,000 stablecoi=
ns are paid back at a dollar, the residual claimant gets whatever the Bitco=
in is worth above that. If Bitcoin goes to $100,000, the residual claimant =
ends up owning $75,000 worth of Bitcoin after paying off $25,000 worth of s=
tablecoins (and makes a $45,000 profit). If Bitcoin goes to $30,000, the re=
sidual claimant ends up owning $5,000 worth (and losing $25,000). If Bitcoi=
n goes to $20,000 the residual claimant is wiped out and the stablecoins ar=
e no longer stable but what are the odds of that.</li></ol><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">My point here was, one, to explain that this basic approach =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0tranching of a risky asset into junior and senior claims =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0is the main move in traditional finance, and that combinations =
and variations on this move are most of what the financial system does. Two=
, I wanted to explain some of the advantages and disadvantages of this appr=
oach compared to the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>main method of making a stabl=
ecoin, which is to sell 25,000 dollar stablecoins for cash and put the $25,=
000 you raise into a traditional dollar bank account (or, more realisticall=
y, use it to buy safe dollar-denominated assets like commercial paper or Tr=
easury bills). The main advantage of the Bitcoin-based approach (call it an=
 =E2=80=9Covercollateralized stablecoin=E2=80=9D) is that it manufactures s=
tablecoins out of pure crypto, without too much of an interface with the tr=
aditional banking system; if you don=E2=80=99t trust banks to hold your dol=
lars, this seems preferable. The main disadvantage is that it manufactures =
stablecoins out of pure crypto, without any actual dollars; if you don=E2=
=80=99t trust Bitcoin to hold its value, this seems worse.[1]</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My third point was that Tether, the biggest and weirde=
st and most controversial stablecoin, mostly seems to be the=C2=A0<em>other=
=C2=A0</em>kind of stablecoin, call it a =E2=80=9Cbacked stablecoin,=E2=80=
=9D the kind with money in the bank. It advertises that all of its coins ar=
e backed at least 1-for-1 with safe dollar assets. But in fact a (small but=
 interesting) fraction of those =E2=80=9Csafe dollar assets=E2=80=9D are in=
 fact secured loans to crypto companies, secured specifically by=C2=A0<em>c=
ryptocurrency</em>. Tether is mostly (it says) in the business of getting d=
ollars, issuing stablecoins, and putting the dollars in the bank (or Chines=
e commercial paper), but it is also a little bit in the business of getting=
 dollars, issuing stablecoins, and using the dollars to fund levered Bitcoi=
n positions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I neglected to mention tha=
t there are a number of stablecoins that are=C2=A0<em>explicitly, entirely<=
/em>=C2=A0in that business, stablecoins that just=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>ov=
ercollateralized stablecoins. The most famous is probably Dai, the stableco=
in of MakerDAO. =E2=80=9CThe Maker Protocol, also known as the Multi-Collat=
eral Dai (MCD) system, allows users to generate Dai by leveraging collatera=
l assets,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/25302980.283824/aHR0cHM6Ly9tYWtlcmRhby5jb20vZW4vd2hpdGVwYXBlciNkYWktYXMtYS=
11bml0LW9mLWFjY291bnQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB688ac75c" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says its w=
hite paper</a>. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25=
302980.283824/aHR0cHM6Ly9tYWtlcmRhby5jb20vZW4vd2hpdGVwYXBlciNjb2xsYXRlcmFsL=
WFzc2V0cw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0dc68165" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">And</a>:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dai is generated, backed, and kept stable th=
rough collateral assets that are deposited into Maker Vaults on the Maker P=
rotocol. A collateral asset is a digital asset that MKR holders have voted =
to accept into the Protocol.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To generate Da=
i, the Maker Protocol accepts as collateral any Ethereum-based asset that h=
as been approved by MKR holders. MKR holders must also approve specific, co=
rresponding Risk Parameters for each accepted collateral (e.g., more stable=
 assets might get more lenient Risk Parameters, while more risky assets cou=
ld get stricter Risk Parameters). Detailed information on Risk Parameters i=
s below. These and other decisions of MKR holders are made through the Make=
r decentralized governance process.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25302980.283=
824/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ2VtaW5pLmNvbS9wcmljZXMvZGFpP3V0bV9zb3VyY2U9Z29vZ2xlJnV=
0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1VU0FfU2VhcmNoX1Byb3NwZWN0aW5nX0V4Y2hhbmdlX0RTQV9EQUkmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1jcGMmdXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9MTI5NTQxNDQ0MjQxJnV0bV90ZXJtPSZnY2xpZD1DajBLQ=
1Fqdy00U0xCaENWQVJJc0FDcmhXTFZnOGlVc2Y3ZS1FTGxZMWtEek5iYWwyUWE0bVlGN0FTTjhX=
Ti05R0xvY2ZMQlZWQmM4UENBYUFnekhFQUx3X3djQg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB499b92a=
4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">And</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When a us=
er deposits ETH or any supported ERC20 token into the Maker platform as col=
lateral, Dai is created and loaned to the user at a collateral-to-loan rati=
o of 66%,[2] which increases the supply of Dai.</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">One thing I will say about this is that it is way more tr=
ansparent and straightforward than the picture I tried to paint of Tether a=
s sort of doing some amount of complicated transformation of Bitcoins into =
dollars at some unspecified level of overcollateralization. This is just a =
decentralized platform automatically transforming Ether into dollars at a s=
pecified level of overcollateralization with clearly defined procedures for=
 making sure the collateral is sufficient and for liquidating if it isn=E2=
=80=99t.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other thing I will say is that=
, as a person whose background is in traditional finance, I=C2=A0<em>like=
=C2=A0</em>the opaque mysterious version more? One thing I said on Thursday=
 is:=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A bank makes a bunch=
 of loans in exchange for senior claims on businesses, houses, etc. Then it=
 pools those loans together on its balance sheet and issues a bunch of diff=
erent claims on that balance sheet. The most senior claims, classically, ar=
e =E2=80=9Cbank deposits=E2=80=9D; the most junior claims are =E2=80=9Cequi=
ty=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccapital.=E2=80=9D Some people want to own a bank; t=
hey think that First Bank of X is good at running its business and will gro=
w its assets and improve its margins and its stock will be worth more in th=
e future, so they buy equity (shares of stock) of the bank. Other people, t=
hough, just want to keep their money somewhere safe; they put their deposit=
s in the First Bank of X because they are confident that a dollar deposited=
 in an account there will always be worth a dollar.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The fundamental reason for this confidence is that bank deposits a=
re senior claims (deposits) on a pool of senior claims (loans) on a diversi=
fied set of good assets (businesses, houses). (In modern banking there are =
other reasons =E2=80=94 deposit insurance, etc. =E2=80=94 but this is the f=
undamental reason.) But notice that this is magic: At one end of the proces=
s you have risky businesses, at the other end of the process you have perfe=
ctly safe dollars. Again, this is due in part to deposit insurance and regu=
lation and lenders of last resort, but it is due mainly to the magic of com=
posing senior claims on senior claims. You use seniority to turn risky thin=
gs into safe things.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When I sa=
y =E2=80=9Cthis is magic,=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t just mean =E2=80=9Cthis =
is pretty cool.=E2=80=9D I mean that it feels like magic, that it is a slei=
ght of hand, that to work effectively it demands willing suspension of disb=
elief from its observers, that it requires a mystery.[3] When you open a ba=
nk account, the bank doesn=E2=80=99t tell you =E2=80=9Cwell we have a 9% ca=
pital ratio, so if our loans lose 9% of their value or less your account wi=
ll be money-good, and our loans are made at an average loan-to-value ratio =
of 68%, so if the underlying assets lose 32% of their value or less our loa=
ns will be good, and if you multiply that it means that your cash won=E2=80=
=99t be touched unless the underlying assets lose more than 38% of their va=
lue in a correlated way, which we have calculated has a less than 1-in-1,00=
0,000 chance of happening.=E2=80=9D If your bank told you that you would ne=
ver give them your money. What your bank tells you is =E2=80=9Cif you put a=
 dollar in this account it=E2=80=99s a dollar.=E2=80=9D There are enough la=
yers of opacity between your deposit and the underlying risky assets that y=
ou don=E2=80=99t think of them as being at all connected.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Similarly in crypto. =E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s a thing that is=
 worth a dollar as long as the price of Ether doesn=E2=80=99t fall by more =
than a third=E2=80=9D is quite straightforward and useful but it does focus=
 the mind on the bad outcome; it gives you the recipe for how to break it. =
=E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s a thing that is worth a dollar and never you mind h=
